00:08:42.660 --> 00:08:45.950
So everybody in here should be
familiar with multiple levels of RAID.

00:08:45.960 --> 00:08:48.200
And I'll tell you,
these were the levels that

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:53.120
were initially defined by
Randy Katz at Berkeley in 1987,

00:08:53.120 --> 00:08:56.120
and these are still what
I call the pure RAID levels.

00:08:57.080 --> 00:09:00.380
These can be combined with
other RAID levels in here,

00:09:00.380 --> 00:09:04.380
and there are some fancy RAID levels
that people are looking at today.

00:09:04.380 --> 00:09:06.060
But for the most part,
these are the RAID levels

00:09:06.060 --> 00:09:06.790
that everybody does.

00:09:06.800 --> 00:09:07.860
And what is a RAID level?

00:09:07.860 --> 00:09:11.920
Well, obviously when you start
lowest to highest in number,

00:09:11.920 --> 00:09:17.240
you actually increase in redundancy
or availability and performance.

00:09:17.240 --> 00:09:19.300
If you start with RAID 0, it's striping.

00:09:19.300 --> 00:09:22.200
Not really a true RAID level,
but a lot of people have,

00:09:22.200 --> 00:09:24.740
or still are deploying
striping today for speed,

00:09:24.740 --> 00:09:27.020
because it's one of the
easiest ways to take a number,

00:09:27.020 --> 00:09:30.520
a number of disks, combine them together,
and get performance out of them.

00:09:30.520 --> 00:09:32.520
And then probably the most
popular RAID level that's

00:09:32.520 --> 00:09:33.760
used out there is mirroring.

00:09:33.760 --> 00:09:36.800
This is basically just taking
either one hard drive or a group

00:09:36.800 --> 00:09:40.530
of hard drives and mirroring them,
keeping the same data set between them.

00:09:40.640 --> 00:09:43.100
So if one were to fail,
you'd have another copy of the data.

00:09:43.100 --> 00:09:45.690
This is the photocopy
way of doing things.

00:09:45.700 --> 00:09:47.870
It's not very efficient.

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:49.270
It's kind of wasteful, right?

00:09:49.350 --> 00:09:51.620
If I have a copy of something,
I make a photocopy,

00:09:51.620 --> 00:09:53.180
I wasted two pieces of paper.

00:09:53.180 --> 00:09:54.870
It's the same with mirroring.

00:09:54.960 --> 00:09:59.500
If I have one hard drive, I mirror it,
I used 100% of the second hard

00:09:59.500 --> 00:10:01.430
drive's space for mirroring.

00:10:01.440 --> 00:10:04.300
And then as you move up,
really you get to what I would

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:06.100
consider more efficient RAID levels.

00:10:06.100 --> 00:10:09.240
And the one that we focus on a lot,
and the one we've optimized for,

00:10:09.240 --> 00:10:10.630
is RAID level five.

00:10:10.640 --> 00:10:14.280
And the beauty of RAID level five is
that it's a distributed parity scheme.

00:10:14.280 --> 00:10:18.780
And what we mean by that is we
actually create an algorithm or a

00:10:18.780 --> 00:10:23.320
piece of data on every one of the
hard drives that is a part of the data

00:10:23.320 --> 00:10:24.520
that's on the rest of the hard drives.

00:10:24.520 --> 00:10:28.050
And essentially what that means is
that if you have a hard drive fail,

00:10:28.130 --> 00:10:31.250
we can instantly, virtually on the fly,
recreate that data from

00:10:31.250 --> 00:10:32.800
the remaining hard drives.

00:10:32.800 --> 00:10:36.750
So you'd have to lose a large
number of hard drives before you'd

00:10:36.790 --> 00:10:39.410
actually have a failure or lose data.

00:10:39.450 --> 00:10:43.450
And the problem with RAID five
in the past has been that the

00:10:43.450 --> 00:10:46.110
performance has not been consistent.

00:10:46.260 --> 00:10:48.900
So the read performance is very
similar to that of RAID zero.

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:50.520
It's like striping a bunch of drives.

00:10:50.520 --> 00:10:52.700
The performance is better
than a single hard drive.

00:10:52.700 --> 00:10:55.660
But the write performance,
especially in random writes,

00:10:55.750 --> 00:10:56.840
has been similar.

00:10:56.890 --> 00:10:57.640
It's slower.

00:10:57.660 --> 00:10:59.740
So people who are doing
things like database or

00:10:59.740 --> 00:11:02.590
online transaction processing,
anybody do that type of

00:11:02.590 --> 00:11:04.720
work on their systems?

00:11:04.770 --> 00:11:07.250
So if you're doing that,
you knew that RAID five was

00:11:07.300 --> 00:11:08.950
a bad way to go in the past.

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:10.580
And also,
if you're doing things like video,

00:11:10.580 --> 00:11:12.760
anybody doing video here,
streaming video?

00:11:12.800 --> 00:11:15.070
If you were streaming video,
RAID five was also terrible.

00:11:15.160 --> 00:11:17.060
People went to things like RAID three.

00:11:17.070 --> 00:11:19.560
Or in most cases,
they were just doing RAID zero striping.

00:11:19.570 --> 00:11:21.900
And with XServe RAID,
we really looked at that.

00:11:21.900 --> 00:11:26.300
And we put our team together and built
some really sophisticated algorithms

00:11:26.310 --> 00:11:30.150
and some cache and caching schemes that
really make RAID five faster in most

00:11:30.310 --> 00:11:33.250
cases than any of the other RAID levels,
including RAID zero.

00:11:33.440 --> 00:11:36.460
So our performance is really
quite good in RAID five.

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:38.970
And the protection is really good.

