00:11:48.860 --> 00:11:50.130
think about on a daily basis.

00:11:50.160 --> 00:11:52.650
When we start there,
we have to talk about the three

00:11:52.740 --> 00:11:54.590
different approaches to storage.

00:11:54.660 --> 00:11:57.930
And some of you may not realize
you're actually deploying a number

00:11:57.930 --> 00:12:00.020
of these within your organization.

00:12:00.020 --> 00:12:02.150
The first one is direct attach.

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:05.050
So when we talk about
direct attach storage,

00:12:05.050 --> 00:12:06.120
what is that?

00:12:06.150 --> 00:12:08.930
And there's a lot of different
ways that we look at this.

00:12:09.100 --> 00:12:12.800
The first way to look at it is,
a great example is the Xserve G5.

00:12:12.960 --> 00:12:15.020
It's locally attached hard drives.

00:12:15.050 --> 00:12:19.740
It's the hard drives that are in the
Xserve G5 that become direct attached.

00:12:19.740 --> 00:12:22.980
And for the most part,
this is the way traditional

00:12:22.980 --> 00:12:24.370
storage was done.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:27.860
You bought a server,
you put hard drives in the server,

00:12:27.910 --> 00:12:29.440
and it was a done deal.

00:12:29.440 --> 00:12:32.420
And when you needed more performance,
the servers didn't have

00:12:32.450 --> 00:12:34.460
a lot of performance,
you added servers,

00:12:34.550 --> 00:12:36.290
and therefore you added storage.

00:12:36.290 --> 00:12:37.860
And that's the way things scaled.

00:12:37.860 --> 00:12:39.010
And it kind of looked like this.

00:12:39.040 --> 00:12:42.590
You had a network down at the bottom,
all your clients, and obviously I could

00:12:42.640 --> 00:12:45.670
draw hundreds of clients,
but I'm not that good with drawing.

00:12:45.680 --> 00:12:48.380
And you have Ethernet switches,
those are the gray lines,

00:12:48.390 --> 00:12:50.260
and then you have the two Xserve G5s.

00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:52.660
And in this case,
you could have a terabyte

00:12:52.930 --> 00:12:57.020
and a half of storage online,
assuming you left it all in either JBOD,

00:12:57.030 --> 00:12:59.920
just a bunch of disks,
or a RAID 0 stripe.

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:01.460
So it's quite a bit of storage.

00:13:01.630 --> 00:13:03.610
But the problem is
that it's never enough.

00:13:03.740 --> 00:13:06.210
And so you might take
one of your servers,

00:13:06.210 --> 00:13:09.080
which is a,
let's call it a high-use server.

00:13:09.080 --> 00:13:11.830
This could be your email server,
for instance.

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:17.040
And this could be an Xserve G5,
a Mac OS 10-based server.

00:13:17.040 --> 00:13:19.540
This could be a Windows server
or a Linux server.

00:13:19.540 --> 00:13:21.440
And you're going to add
some external storage.

00:13:21.540 --> 00:13:22.970
Well, that works.

00:13:23.200 --> 00:13:25.290
And you might even find
that with the Xserver RAID,

00:13:25.290 --> 00:13:27.650
because it's a dual ported,
dual controller design,

00:13:27.690 --> 00:13:30.240
that you want to share half of
the storage on one of the boxes

00:13:30.250 --> 00:13:32.000
and half the storage on the other.

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:33.040
A little more efficient.

00:13:33.040 --> 00:13:36.810
You get the ability to centralize your
storage so that you take advantage of

00:13:36.820 --> 00:13:38.980
the high availability of Xserver RAID.

00:13:39.170 --> 00:13:40.990
Yet you get to share it over two servers.

00:13:41.020 --> 00:13:44.660
Or you might find that that's not
enough and you just want to attach more

00:13:44.780 --> 00:13:47.000
storage to your individual servers.

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:48.980
And this is still direct attach.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:51.000
And this is the way
things have been done.

00:13:51.000 --> 00:13:53.000
It's truly a traditional approach.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:57.810
And it works really easily because
today most people have LAN-based backup.

00:13:58.000 --> 00:13:59.950
So you're backing up across the LAN.

00:14:00.080 --> 00:14:04.880
Now this was a really good idea
when the data sets were small.

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:08.900
How many people can remember a couple
years ago when your entire organization

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:08.900
ran on a couple hundred servers?

00:14:08.900 --> 00:14:10.890
100 gigabytes, right?

00:14:10.910 --> 00:14:16.900
I had an experience a few months
ago when GarageBand first came out.

00:14:16.900 --> 00:14:21.900
And I was actually on a plane and I went
to install GarageBand on my notebook.

00:14:21.900 --> 00:14:24.900
And I put the CD in and
I went to install it.

00:14:24.900 --> 00:14:25.900
Actually the DVD.

00:14:25.900 --> 00:14:28.900
And it said that I didn't
have enough room.

00:14:28.900 --> 00:14:29.900
And this is my notebook.

00:14:29.900 --> 00:14:31.900
And I thought, don't I have an 80 gig
hard drive in here?

00:14:31.900 --> 00:14:35.890
Well, I had a few keynote presentations
so it was a little hard to do.

00:14:35.950 --> 00:14:38.300
But for the most part,
backing this amount of

00:14:38.380 --> 00:14:38.800
storage is really easy.

00:14:38.800 --> 00:14:39.790
It's a lot of data.

00:14:39.870 --> 00:14:41.760
In this case, we would have almost seven
terabytes of data here.

00:14:41.810 --> 00:14:43.770
Imagine backing that up across LAN.

00:14:43.840 --> 00:14:46.790
Anybody go to the backup
session earlier this week?

00:14:46.800 --> 00:14:47.800
So you get an idea.

00:14:47.800 --> 00:14:51.800
For those of you who didn't go and
those of you who backup terabytes,

00:14:51.800 --> 00:14:55.750
it can really take about,
in an uncompressed environment,

00:14:56.070 --> 00:14:58.800
over 24 hours to backup
a terabyte of storage.

00:14:58.800 --> 00:15:01.800
So, you know,
the backup windows are shrinking.

00:15:01.800 --> 00:15:06.330
So this LAN-based backup doesn't seem
to work very well in this occasion

00:15:06.440 --> 00:15:08.700
where you have a lot of storage.

00:15:08.700 --> 00:15:12.250
So when you start looking at this,
you go, well, one of the problems is

00:15:12.250 --> 00:15:15.690
I need to share the storage,
but I have something like this

00:15:15.700 --> 00:15:16.690
where I'm pretty dedicated.

00:15:16.700 --> 00:15:19.880
That one XSERV RAID,
let's call it 3.5 terabytes,

00:15:19.880 --> 00:15:21.540
is dedicated to that server.

00:15:21.700 --> 00:15:24.680
And the other XSERV RAID is
dedicated to the other server.

00:15:24.730 --> 00:15:27.430
So my resource sharing is limited.

00:15:27.820 --> 00:15:31.680
So I better guess right as to how much
storage I really need on each server.

00:15:31.850 --> 00:15:34.140
Let's say one of those servers
needed 6 terabytes and the

00:15:34.230 --> 00:15:35.670
other one needed 1 terabyte.

00:15:35.800 --> 00:15:38.600
In the direct-attached world,
it's really hard to do, right?

00:15:38.600 --> 00:15:41.570
You just can't,
what we'll call provisioning that

00:15:41.880 --> 00:15:44.380
storage over between the two systems.

00:15:44.500 --> 00:15:47.330
So when you look at this and you
look at that traditional approach,

00:15:47.620 --> 00:15:49.390
is it still viable in today's world?

00:15:49.500 --> 00:15:51.390
And a lot of people
look at it and they say,

00:15:51.500 --> 00:15:54.460
sure, it's viable because it's a
lower initial investment.

00:15:54.560 --> 00:15:56.500
I don't have to do much planning.

00:15:56.500 --> 00:15:58.500
I know that I can just
buy one and attach it.

00:15:58.500 --> 00:16:02.500
But there are problems with scalability
and there's problems with longevity.

00:16:02.500 --> 00:16:06.560
Because a lot of times that storage
is internal to your servers and when

00:16:06.740 --> 00:16:10.400
it's time to replace the server,
when the call kicks in,

00:16:10.400 --> 00:16:12.280
it's time to replace that server,
you end up not having

00:16:12.280 --> 00:16:13.400
storage that's compatible.

00:16:13.470 --> 00:16:16.820
And that's the beauty of an SSRV RAID if
you deploy it because it's external,

00:16:16.840 --> 00:16:18.380
it's fiber channel,
it's just going to plug in.

00:16:18.400 --> 00:16:22.750
But you also find out that
you're pretty limited on that

00:16:22.750 --> 00:16:25.400
backup and that restoration.

00:16:25.450 --> 00:16:28.400
So it's not really the ideal approach.

00:16:28.400 --> 00:16:29.400
So what else do you do?

00:16:29.570 --> 00:16:31.400
Well, this is what most people do.

00:16:31.400 --> 00:16:33.380
Most people have moved to a
network-attached storage model.

00:16:33.400 --> 00:16:37.210
They start out with some type of
direct-attach and usually it's many more

00:16:37.210 --> 00:16:38.400
than two servers that are out there.

00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:41.340
And they take some
type of direct-attached

00:16:41.440 --> 00:16:44.280
NAS right onto the network.

00:16:44.330 --> 00:16:48.300
So it's attaching to that gray wire
that's there indicating our network.

00:16:48.300 --> 00:16:51.090
And in my case,
I chose to take an XSRV G5

00:16:51.150 --> 00:16:54.300
and an XSRV RAID and use
that as a NAS replacement.

00:16:54.300 --> 00:16:55.160
And that works.

00:16:55.380 --> 00:16:58.970
It works and it gives you the
ability to share that storage

00:16:58.990 --> 00:17:01.300
across the network to both servers.

00:17:01.310 --> 00:17:05.300
So you get some provisioning because
what you can do is you can dedicate,

00:17:05.300 --> 00:17:06.280
you don't have to
dedicate those resources,

00:17:06.290 --> 00:17:08.300
you can leave them open.

00:17:08.300 --> 00:17:10.200
And it has expandability.

00:17:10.200 --> 00:17:12.810
But the expandability becomes
limited because what happens

00:17:12.810 --> 00:17:16.200
at this point is now the wire
that's coming out of the XSRV G5,

00:17:16.200 --> 00:17:19.200
that single Ethernet
becomes the bottleneck.

00:17:19.450 --> 00:17:23.330
And because your backbone,
unless you're building a 10

00:17:23.550 --> 00:17:27.200
gigabit fiber backbone or just
10 gigabit Ethernet backbone,

00:17:27.200 --> 00:17:30.090
you're really pretty limited in the
overall performance it's going to do.

00:17:30.340 --> 00:17:34.010
How many people have a 4 gigabit
Ethernet backbone out there?

00:17:34.200 --> 00:17:36.200
How about a 10?

00:17:36.200 --> 00:17:38.200
So I saw one hand.

00:17:38.200 --> 00:17:40.100
How many, you're pretty much limited.

00:17:40.100 --> 00:17:42.100
How many people have gigabit backbone?

00:17:42.100 --> 00:17:43.930
That's just about everybody out here.

00:17:44.180 --> 00:17:48.220
So imagine that if each XSRV G5
can saturate that gigabit backbone,

00:17:48.220 --> 00:17:51.070
how is your storage being
attached going to do that?

00:17:51.100 --> 00:17:53.100
And this is really what most people do.

00:17:53.100 --> 00:17:57.100
Most people have deployed a network
attached specialty appliance.

00:17:57.120 --> 00:17:59.090
And they're just an embedded NAS.

00:17:59.160 --> 00:18:01.100
So this is a very lightweight NAS server.

00:18:01.100 --> 00:18:04.090
And the reason they've done this is
there's no client access licenses,

00:18:04.090 --> 00:18:06.100
just like an XSRV G5.

00:18:06.100 --> 00:18:08.100
But they're usually inexpensive.

00:18:08.100 --> 00:18:10.000
And usually what happens
is you end up with this.

00:18:10.150 --> 00:18:13.000
And you end up with a lot of
different little appliances out there.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:17.000
And the problem with that is that while
it gives you a heterogeneous approach,

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:20.880
and while it has a lower investment,
it is a management nightmare.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:23.000
And it's very difficult to manage that.

00:18:23.000 --> 00:18:24.840
And it's very difficult
to know what's failed.

00:18:25.130 --> 00:18:27.000
And you find that you start
plugging them in all over.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:32.000
And when you have an Ethernet problem,
it's really a problem.

00:18:32.100 --> 00:18:34.880
It is a big problem because you
lose accessibility to the storage.

00:18:35.360 --> 00:18:38.000
And whether we like it or not,
anybody here ever crimp

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:38.000
an Ethernet cable?

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:39.880
Okay,
if you've crimped an Ethernet cable,

00:18:39.950 --> 00:18:42.900
you know that usually one out of
three you're going to screw up.

00:18:42.900 --> 00:18:45.900
And usually it fails like six months
later when it's hanging there.

00:18:45.900 --> 00:18:48.900
And this is part of the problem with
hanging everything on the network.

00:18:48.900 --> 00:18:50.900
That network was made to
deliver small packets.

00:18:50.900 --> 00:18:54.890
And it wasn't really made to deliver
the performance and the reliability

00:18:54.900 --> 00:18:56.900
to a lot of different servers.

00:18:56.900 --> 00:18:58.900
It is truly a collision-based network.

00:18:58.900 --> 00:19:00.900
But for most people, that works.

00:19:00.900 --> 00:19:05.890
And in fact, most people who start
there tend to move to this,

00:19:06.040 --> 00:19:07.900
the NAS appliances.

00:19:07.900 --> 00:19:09.900
And we know who they are.

00:19:09.900 --> 00:19:13.880
They're generally extremely
expensive in a per-gigabyte cost.

00:19:13.960 --> 00:19:15.900
But they have a lot of features.

00:19:15.900 --> 00:19:18.650
They do things like snapshotting,
which means that you can

00:19:18.650 --> 00:19:19.820
replicate the data really quickly.

00:19:19.930 --> 00:19:21.860
And they're appliance-like.

00:19:21.920 --> 00:19:23.900
They're generally easy deployment.

00:19:23.900 --> 00:19:25.840
They have a built-in file system.

00:19:26.020 --> 00:19:29.040
And for the most part,
these very high-end appliances have

00:19:29.160 --> 00:19:31.900
an operating system and a file system.

00:19:31.900 --> 00:19:37.790
And they also have the downside
of being a single-vendor lock-in.

00:19:37.830 --> 00:19:39.730
You're, for the most part,
using their management tools

00:19:39.810 --> 00:19:41.800
and you're having to buy them
again and again and again.

00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:43.750
And it gets pretty expensive.

00:19:43.800 --> 00:19:45.800
And we all know those people.

00:19:45.800 --> 00:19:47.800
And they're good things.

00:19:47.800 --> 00:19:49.800
They're companies like
Network Appliance and EMC.

00:19:49.880 --> 00:19:51.800
They build really nice products.

00:19:51.830 --> 00:19:56.080
And they still have the issue
of having that single point

00:19:56.080 --> 00:19:58.640
of connectivity to Ethernet.

00:19:58.960 --> 00:20:00.920
Now,
they may have multiple Ethernet ports,

00:20:01.100 --> 00:20:03.780
but generally, you're not going to have
hundreds of Ethernet switches.

00:20:03.850 --> 00:20:06.720
You're going to have one or
two very high-end switches.

00:20:06.800 --> 00:20:07.700
And what if you don't have a hundred?

00:20:07.700 --> 00:20:09.600
You're going to have a
high-end infrastructure.

00:20:09.600 --> 00:20:11.600
You're really funneling
everything through Gigabit.

00:20:11.600 --> 00:20:15.590
Has anybody here ever seen Gigabit
Ethernet perform at Gigabit?

00:20:15.600 --> 00:20:19.600
So, that's one of the other issues
that we run into all the time.

00:20:19.600 --> 00:20:20.570
So, what is the choice?

00:20:20.620 --> 00:20:22.590
The choice is to build a SAN.

00:20:22.610 --> 00:20:25.090
And it sounds like a lot of people
out here have already taken that step,

00:20:25.090 --> 00:20:25.480
at least.

00:20:25.600 --> 00:20:29.570
So, what does a basic SAN look
like and where do they scale?

00:20:29.700 --> 00:20:31.550
Well,
most people who build a SAN start out

00:20:31.550 --> 00:20:33.550
again with that direct-attached model.

00:20:33.620 --> 00:20:37.600
They start out there
and they add storage.

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:40.980
And I'm going to go in a fiber
channel switch in here because

00:20:40.980 --> 00:20:42.500
I knew I was building a SAN.

00:20:42.500 --> 00:20:46.500
So, from a best practices standpoint,
I want to start out with expandability

00:20:46.500 --> 00:20:48.500
and scalability already in there.

00:20:48.500 --> 00:20:53.500
And you can take an XSERV RAID today and
you can use a tool called LUN masking.

00:20:53.560 --> 00:20:56.500
And you can map each address,
almost like a MAC address,

00:20:56.500 --> 00:21:00.490
but we call it a fiber
channel worldwide port name.

00:21:00.630 --> 00:21:04.150
And we would map those worldwide
port names very easily in the

00:21:04.150 --> 00:21:06.500
RAID admin utility to each server.

00:21:06.500 --> 00:21:08.390
So, we can have a provisioned
storage to each server.

00:21:08.420 --> 00:21:11.200
So, the servers can't see
each other's storage,

00:21:11.200 --> 00:21:13.400
but they see the storage they have.

00:21:13.400 --> 00:21:15.400
Really simple implementation.

00:21:15.400 --> 00:21:17.400
And I can add more.

00:21:17.400 --> 00:21:19.410
And as I add more,
I don't degrade my performance

00:21:19.410 --> 00:21:22.040
because my back channel network
is a specialized network called

00:21:22.290 --> 00:21:23.390
fiber channel in this case.

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:28.110
And fiber channel is a non-blocking
network infrastructure and my

00:21:28.110 --> 00:21:31.400
performance scales as my capacity scales.

00:21:31.450 --> 00:21:33.320
And we call that a SAN island.

00:21:33.430 --> 00:21:35.250
And then people will scale it out.

00:21:35.440 --> 00:21:38.370
So, as you scale it out,
the server becomes more heterogeneous.

00:21:38.430 --> 00:21:41.400
The servers become MACs, PCs, Linux.

00:21:41.400 --> 00:21:43.400
Hopefully they're all MACs.

00:21:43.400 --> 00:21:46.400
But as you scale it out,
now you can start to deploy more storage

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:49.400
on more servers and you're not limited.

00:21:49.400 --> 00:21:51.400
And you can reprovision
that storage as you need to.

00:21:51.400 --> 00:21:53.400
And in some cases, the manual process.

00:21:53.400 --> 00:21:56.380
In other cases,
there are partners that can help us

00:21:56.440 --> 00:22:01.490
provision that storage instantaneously
and without any interruption of service.

00:22:01.700 --> 00:28:03.800
[Transcript missing]

00:28:03.900 --> 00:30:27.800
[Transcript missing]

00:30:27.880 --> 00:30:30.000
If we look at that mission-critical
storage environment,

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:33.060
I picked one, an interesting one here,
because I said I'm not

00:30:33.060 --> 00:30:34.120
going to pick one on Macs.

00:30:34.180 --> 00:30:36.080
I'm going to pick one on Windows.

00:30:36.080 --> 00:30:40.810
So this is a Windows 2003 advanced server
with Microsoft clustering environment.

00:30:40.820 --> 00:30:43.870
In this case,
it cost about $6 a gigabyte to deliver

00:30:44.180 --> 00:30:46.920
fully redundant mission-critical storage.

00:30:46.920 --> 00:30:50.700
And this is something that today you'd
have to spend an incredible amount of

00:30:50.700 --> 00:30:52.950
money to deliver this with other systems.

00:30:52.960 --> 00:30:55.670
And this is really made
possible by Xserve RAID.

00:30:56.170 --> 00:30:59.380
So in this case, you've got a lot of
storage to two servers,

00:30:59.380 --> 00:31:01.740
and it's really simple
and easy to deploy.

00:31:03.460 --> 00:31:06.190
Now here's your typical three-tier
storage infrastructure the

00:31:06.190 --> 00:31:07.900
way it usually really looks.

00:31:07.950 --> 00:31:11.600
It's more than one storage device,
it's more than one server,

00:31:11.640 --> 00:31:12.900
and it's heterogeneous.

00:31:12.950 --> 00:31:16.200
And so you do have a storage
pool that's mission critical,

00:31:16.220 --> 00:31:18.660
a business critical pool,
and a near-line pool.

00:31:18.710 --> 00:31:19.820
That's really the way it looks.

00:31:19.890 --> 00:31:24.540
And today, with XSAN, you can build this.

00:31:24.580 --> 00:31:28.230
Or at least when XSAN is released,
I should say.

00:31:29.410 --> 00:31:32.180
So it all comes down to which
storage approach is best,

00:31:32.180 --> 00:31:33.490
and it really depends.

00:31:33.600 --> 00:31:35.890
And what it depends on

00:31:36.140 --> 00:32:03.000
The other thing that's interesting
is that 50% of the managers

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:06.890
consider heterogeneous storage
to be a strategic goal for them.

00:32:06.920 --> 00:32:10.060
So when we talk about interoperability,
this is important.

00:32:10.080 --> 00:32:12.820
So if you don't have an
all Apple infrastructure,

00:32:12.820 --> 00:32:16.630
you don't have an all Windows or an all
Linux or an all Solaris infrastructure,

00:32:16.630 --> 00:32:18.170
you really need to be heterogeneous.

00:32:18.170 --> 00:32:22.670
And I think the most important thing
is that 52% of the people surveyed,

00:32:22.670 --> 00:32:26.110
and I think they surveyed
about 1,000 IT managers,

00:32:26.410 --> 00:32:30.140
they view the reduced maintenance costs
as proof of a return on investment.

00:32:30.140 --> 00:32:33.160
So when you look at
deploying tiered storage,

00:32:33.160 --> 00:32:37.620
probably in that high tier of
storage that's 40 to $100 a gigabyte,

00:32:37.640 --> 00:32:39.890
you pay that same amount
in maintenance every year.

00:32:39.900 --> 00:32:42.480
And that's really where the cost is.

00:32:42.480 --> 00:32:44.220
So when you look at, well,
I can tier this,

00:32:44.360 --> 00:32:47.240
and I can reduce my cost both in
the initial cost of the system

00:32:47.240 --> 00:32:50.190
and in the maintenance cost,
that's really what it's all about.

00:32:50.190 --> 00:32:51.900
And can I deliver those same services?

00:32:51.900 --> 00:32:53.230
We think so.

00:32:53.240 --> 00:32:56.910
So if you're doing storage planning,
there's a few things to look at.

00:32:57.190 --> 00:32:59.510
It's really, well,
what do I already have?

00:32:59.510 --> 00:33:00.850
What do I really need?

00:33:00.850 --> 00:33:02.620
How much is it going to cost?

00:33:02.660 --> 00:33:04.140
And so let's take a
look at some of those.

00:33:04.600 --> 00:33:06.350
The first one is existing infrastructure.

00:33:06.500 --> 00:33:08.920
There's two things that
people don't look at here.

00:33:09.090 --> 00:33:12.060
The first one is,
how old is the existing infrastructure?

00:33:12.110 --> 00:33:15.990
I hear this term all the time,
and I guarantee everyone in this audience

00:33:15.990 --> 00:33:18.080
has used it in storage at least once.

00:33:18.140 --> 00:33:19.620
It's called legacy.

00:33:19.620 --> 00:33:22.100
They all say,
I have legacy storage that I need

00:33:22.170 --> 00:33:24.480
to connect to my new storage.

00:33:24.510 --> 00:33:25.820
Anybody ever say that?

00:33:26.030 --> 00:33:27.300
Yeah, we say it a lot, right?

00:33:27.300 --> 00:33:28.030
Legacy storage.

00:33:28.100 --> 00:33:29.300
Well, what does that mean?

00:33:29.300 --> 00:33:31.080
Does anybody here realize
storage wears out?

00:33:31.130 --> 00:33:34.000
I mean, that's another thing that
people don't realize.

00:33:34.000 --> 00:33:37.720
In the year 2000, I paid $2 million for
this three-letter acronym,

00:33:37.720 --> 00:33:38.380
storage.

00:33:38.380 --> 00:33:41.300
And I have to amortize it
over the next 10 years because

00:33:41.300 --> 00:33:42.410
I paid a lot of money for it.

00:33:42.660 --> 00:33:43.830
Well, storage wears out.

00:33:43.860 --> 00:33:44.990
It's rotating media.

00:33:44.990 --> 00:33:48.060
It's not as bad as tires on a car,
but it does wear out.

00:33:48.060 --> 00:33:51.170
So you have to plan on depreciating
that storage over three to five

00:33:51.200 --> 00:33:52.590
years and getting it out of there.

00:33:52.600 --> 00:33:54.570
And when you do,
are you going to buy that same

00:33:54.760 --> 00:33:57.700
monolithic storage you bought before,
or are you going to look differently?

00:33:57.700 --> 00:34:02.030
The other thing to really look at is,
have you considered a tiered approach,

00:34:02.390 --> 00:34:06.080
lowering the overall cost of storage,
putting that expensive storage in

00:34:06.080 --> 00:34:09.130
your mission-critical areas and
putting lower-cost storage in the

00:34:09.130 --> 00:34:10.840
business-critical and the near line?

00:34:10.910 --> 00:34:12.580
It's something to really consider.

00:34:12.580 --> 00:34:15.460
And then the other one is
true capacity requirements.

00:34:15.460 --> 00:34:19.280
And since most of us don't really know
what our requirements are going to be,

00:34:19.280 --> 00:34:20.180
we can take a guess.

00:34:20.340 --> 00:34:22.140
But, you know,
who would have thought that

00:34:22.490 --> 00:34:27.070
from 1998 to 2003 that storage
would have been growing,

00:34:27.070 --> 00:34:29.400
from a needs standpoint,
110 percent per year?

00:34:29.430 --> 00:34:31.180
Not a lot of people
would have guessed that,

00:34:31.180 --> 00:34:32.790
and they would have guessed low.

00:34:33.000 --> 00:34:35.700
So in deploying something
like a storage area network,

00:34:35.820 --> 00:34:37.700
it allows you to actually
grow with that storage.

00:34:37.700 --> 00:34:41.950
So you get scalability up, down, in, out,
every way you can look at.

00:34:42.150 --> 00:34:44.510
So you can redeploy the
storage and reprovision it.

00:34:44.580 --> 00:34:47.040
So you need to look at
today and look at tomorrow.

00:34:47.090 --> 00:34:49.580
I think the other important
thing is throughput.

00:34:49.730 --> 00:34:52.630
So we talk about network
attach versus storage area

00:34:52.630 --> 00:34:54.220
networks versus direct attach.

00:34:54.220 --> 00:34:57.300
In the storage area network world,
in the direct attach world,

00:34:57.560 --> 00:35:00.620
the performance is going to be
bottlenecked by the limitation of

00:35:00.620 --> 00:35:02.430
either the server or the storage.

00:35:02.500 --> 00:35:04.440
They're the limitations.

00:35:04.500 --> 00:35:09.010
In the network attach model,
the throughput or the storage performance

00:35:09.100 --> 00:35:10.930
is going to be limited by the network.

00:35:10.940 --> 00:35:13.330
So you have to determine
what is my application.

00:35:13.620 --> 00:35:14.810
Is it megabytes per second?

00:35:14.810 --> 00:35:15.810
Is it IOs per second?

00:35:15.820 --> 00:35:17.950
And how many clients do
I actually have out there?

00:35:18.010 --> 00:35:19.840
So you really have to look at that.

00:35:19.910 --> 00:35:22.900
The other one is really
availability requirements.

00:35:22.970 --> 00:35:25.420
Do I need it to really
be up 24 hours a day,

00:35:25.560 --> 00:35:28.030
seven days a week with no downtime?

00:35:28.030 --> 00:35:31.680
Or can I have a reasonable
two to four hour downtime?

00:35:31.710 --> 00:35:34.440
It could be five minutes,
but let's just assume it's four o'clock

00:35:34.560 --> 00:35:38.400
in the morning and something happens and
it's going to be two hours of downtime.

00:35:38.430 --> 00:35:40.560
Is that reasonable?

00:35:40.560 --> 00:35:42.240
Is it business critical?

00:35:42.280 --> 00:35:43.540
Does it need to be archived?

00:35:43.540 --> 00:35:45.240
How often does it need to be archived?

00:35:45.320 --> 00:35:46.720
Can I use near line?

00:35:46.720 --> 00:35:50.400
These are all questions you have to ask
and you have to answer these yourself

00:35:50.520 --> 00:35:52.800
because there's really no one who
can tell you what your business model

00:35:52.800 --> 00:35:54.720
looks like because they vary so much.

00:35:54.760 --> 00:35:56.480
In fact,
you'll find that most of the people

00:35:56.480 --> 00:36:00.180
selling very high end storage will
dictate your business model to you.

00:36:00.180 --> 00:36:01.180
And that's not necessarily
the right way to do it.

00:36:01.180 --> 00:36:06.500
And the other one is
really disaster recovery.

00:36:06.500 --> 00:36:09.180
So there's been a couple things
that have really driven that.

00:36:09.200 --> 00:36:12.950
One, of course,
was 9/11 and none of us really wanted

00:36:13.010 --> 00:36:16.870
that to happen and none of us wanted to
have to bear what happened afterward and

00:36:16.870 --> 00:36:19.270
that was rethink our storage strategy.

00:36:19.330 --> 00:36:20.780
Let's get this off site.

00:36:20.780 --> 00:36:22.240
And there's really two ways to do it.

00:36:22.240 --> 00:36:24.360
One is to deploy remote replication.

00:36:24.480 --> 00:36:25.290
Very expensive.

00:36:25.290 --> 00:36:28.350
Generally, it doubles your cost because
not only do you usually have

00:36:28.440 --> 00:36:30.140
