00:56:29.140 --> 00:56:32.940
And for those of you that aren't
familiar with the process,

00:56:32.940 --> 00:56:37.790
when you bring a server up and down
on a SAN or reboot a server on a SAN,

00:56:37.800 --> 00:56:41.850
something called an RSCN,
a Registered State Change Notification,

00:56:41.910 --> 00:56:42.500
goes out.

00:56:42.540 --> 00:56:45.360
And what that is,
is that server telling every

00:56:45.670 --> 00:56:49.280
other server on the SAN,
hey, I'm here or I'm gone.

00:56:50.070 --> 00:56:52.060
Well, when that happens,
it's only a split second.

00:56:52.060 --> 00:56:59.070
But if you have server A talking to disk
A and server B reboots and comes back up,

00:56:59.070 --> 00:57:04.410
and this RSCN goes around the SAN fabric,
server A momentarily pauses.

00:57:04.420 --> 00:57:09.160
If you're in an OLTP environment running
a database or something like that,

00:57:09.480 --> 00:57:10.840
not really a big deal.

00:57:10.860 --> 00:57:14.150
If you're streaming video or
you're streaming a backup and

00:57:14.150 --> 00:57:18.490
all of a sudden there's a pause,
what do you think happens to the screen?

00:57:20.780 --> 00:57:24.200
This is not a good thing if you're
doing high-definition broadcast.

00:57:24.320 --> 00:57:28.250
So this feature that we have
called I/O Stream Guard allows

00:57:28.260 --> 00:57:33.000
that switch port to not acknowledge
something called an RSCN.

00:57:33.130 --> 00:57:37.660
That way you can have continuous
streaming video or streaming backup

00:57:37.670 --> 00:57:40.060
without having that port go down.

